\section{Metatheory} \label{sec:metatheory}

The rules of our rewrite semantics can be applied anywhere,
in any order, and they give meaning to programs without
committing to a particular evaluation strategy.
%
But then it had better be the case that no matter how the
rules are applied, one always obtains the same result!
%
If the rewrite rules were terminating, then we would expect
that all possible execution paths lead to the same normal form.
%
However, since \calcname has recursion, we instead show that
the rules are \emph{confluent}.
%
% which means that whenever
% $e_2 \movesfrom^\ast e_1 \ movesto^\ast e_3$,
% there exists a $e_4$ so that $e_2 \movesto^\ast e_4 \movesfrom^\ast e_3$.

\subsection{Confluence}

\mypara{Reductions and Confluence}
%
A \emph{reduction} \rr is a binary relation on a set of terms \univ.
%
We write $\rr^{k}$ for the $k$-step closure of $\rr$ and $\rr^{*}$
for the reflexive and transitive closure of $\rr$, \ie $\rr^{*} \equiv \cup_{0 \leq k} \rr^k$.
%
We write $\rstep{\rr}{e}{e'}$ ($a$ \emph{steps to} $b$) if $(e, e') \in \rr$ and
$\rsteps{\rr}{e}{e'}$ ($a$ \emph{reduces to} $b$) if $(e, e') \in \rr^{*}$.
%
A reduction $\rr$ is \emph{confluent} if whenever $\rsteps{\rr}{e}{e_1}$ and $\rsteps{\rr}{e}{e_2}$,
there exists an $e'$ such that $\rsteps{\rr}{e_1}{e'}$ and $\rsteps{\rr}{e_2}{e'}$.
%
Confluence gives us the assurance that we will not get
different results when choosing different rules, or get
stuck with some rules and not with others.

\mypara{Normal Forms}
%
A term $e$ is an $\rr$-\emph{Normal Form} if there does
not exist any $e'$ such that $\rstep{\rr}{e}{e'}$.
Confluence implies that ultimately, rewriting terminates
with at most one unique normal form, regardless of the
evaluation strategy \cite{Barendregt}.

\begin{lemma}[Unicity] \label{lem:nf}
If $\rr$ is confluent then every term reduces to at most one normal form.
\end{lemma}

Our main result is that the reduction relation $\rr$ for \calcname,
defined as the union of the reduction relations
$\runi$ (Unification),
$\rapp$ ($\beta$-Application),
$\rcon$ (Conjunction),
$\rgc$  (Garbage Collection),
$\rfail$ (Fail Propagation) and
$\rspc$ (Speculation)
in \cref{FIXME} % \cref{fig:rulesI}
is confluent.

\begin{theorem}[Confluence] \label{thm:confluence}
The reduction relation $\rr \equiv \runi \cup \rapp \cup \rcon \cup \rgc \cup \rfail$ is confluent.
\end{theorem}

A reduction $R$ \emph{commutes} with $S$ if for all terms
$e, e_1, e_2$ such that $\rsteps{R}{e}{e_1}$ and $\rsteps{S}{e}{e_2}$
there exists $e'$ such that $\rsteps{S}{e_1}{e'}$ and $\rsteps{R}{e_2}{e'}$.
%
We establish confluence by proving each sub-relation is confluent,
and that they pairwise commute \cite{Huet}.

\begin{lemma}[Commutativity] \label{lem:comm}
If $R$ and $S$ are confluent and commute, then $R \cup S$ is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\subsection{Design}

\calcname's rewrite rules we carefully designed to ensure confluence.
%
\calcname layers values into \emph{scalars} (integers, variables)
and \emph{heap values} (tuples and $\lambda$-terms) and then only
allows scalars (no tuples or $\lambda$-terms) in tuples
to ensure confluence.
%
Further, the \rulename{deref-h} rule prevents substituting heap values
under $\lambda$ and tuples, and prevents ``copying'' heap values
in constraints as all of these lead to non-confluence.

\mypara{Non-Confluence}
Suppose we eliminated \rulename{deref-h} and instead used a single
rule like \rulename{deref-s} for \emph{all} values.
%
Then we could substitute $\lambda$ under tuples (and tuples under $\lambda$)
which would violate confluence as shown by the following example.
%
\begin{verbatim}
ex x,y. x = <1,y>; y = \z.x; x
-->> ex x. x = <1, \z.x>; x         (1)

ex x,y. x = <1,y>; y = \z.x; x
-->> ex x. y = \z.<1, y>; <1, y>    (2)
\end{verbatim}
%
(A similar phenomenon arises just with inlining mutually recursive
$\lambda$-terms~\cite{Ariola2002}.)

\mypara{Divergence: JB on Slack}
%
Even just substituting tuple under tuple can lead to non-termination
which breaks the confluence via Newman's lemma route for the
unification-rules fragment. Note we need termination as we can only
directly prove \emph{local} confluence for the unification reductions
as \cref{lem:join-h-h} requires multiple steps to reach a peak.

\begin{verbatim}
    ex x, y. x = <1,y>; y = <2,x>; x
--> ex x, y. x = <1,y>; y = <2,x>; <1,y>
--> ex x, y. x = <1,y>; y = <2,x>; <1,<2,x>>
--> ex x, y. x = <1,y>; y = <2,x>; <1,<2,<1,y>>>
--> ...
\end{verbatim}


Value stratification is not a limitation: in essence we ANF to name the
inner elements (tuples or $\lambda$-terms), and then use the
unification rule \rulename{utup} to destruct or ``unpack'' the
tuple and to access its contents.
%
However, not substituting under lambda is a tiresome restriction: e.g.,
